Zig does **not** have a dedicated "parameterized test" feature. The idiomatic approach is to use `inline for` over a tuple of test cases inside a `test` block. The relevant section is:

**[Zig Language Reference — inline for](https://ziglang.org/documentation/master/#inline-for)**

```zig
test "parameterized" {
    const cases = .{
        .{ 1, 2, 3 },
        .{ 10, 20, 30 },
    };
    inline for (cases) |case| {
        try std.testing.expectEqual(case[2], case[0] + case[1]);
    }
}
```

`inline for` unrolls at comptime, so each tuple element becomes its own check. You can also use `comptime` blocks or `anytype` function parameters to generalize test helpers across types. There is no built-in `@parameterizedTest` or similar construct.
